{
  "doc_id": "36812",
  "text": "More unambiguous studies have implicated microglia in developmental cell death of distinct retinal cell subsets. The majority of retina neuron and glia types are born in excess numbers and undergo a period of cell death from P0 to P13 [CITATION_1] . While programed cell death accounts for the majority of this process [CITATION_2] , microglia-mediated phagocytosis plays a role in some cases. Depletion of microglia via the CX3CR1-CreER-iDTR system reduces astrocyte cell death, leading to anatomical changes in astrocyte distribution [CITATION_3] . Similarly, microglia depletion in Csf1r −/− mice increased the developmental density of a subset of RGCs, and complement mediated engulfment was implicated in this process [CITATION_4] . Though the evidence is more limited, microglia may also be involved in initiating, sensing, or responding to canonical neural apoptosis. In the developing brain, 60% of Purkinje cells that undergo apoptosis were engulfed by or in contact with microglia [CITATION_5] , and developmental neuronal death appeared to facilitate microglia entry and positioning into the developing zebrafish brain [CITATION_6] . The list of molecular pathways that facilitate microglia-mediated phagocytosis of neurons or CNS debris is quite extensive ( Table 3 ) and includes synaptotagmin-11 (Syt11, [CITATION_7] ), G proteincoupled receptor 34 (GPR34, [CITATION_8] ), Mer tyrosine kinase (MerTK, [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] ) and spleen tyrosine kinase (Syk, [CITATION_12] ). It remains to be determined whether these pathways converge on a central microglia phagocytic process or whether their use is context dependent.",
